# hilavitkutin-providers

Default Resource-backed providers for the hilavitkutin scheduler.
The crate ships Kit impls consumers wire onto the
`SchedulerBuilder` via `add_kit`, producing
`Resource<T>` registrations the engine then dispatches through
WorkUnit Context bounds. Standalone ecosystem crate: consumed by
the engine via Kit installation, no reverse dep.

v0 covers the interner. Future modules (ColumnStorage default,
Clock default, MemoryProvider default for libc/Unix) land in
their own rounds when an actual consumer surfaces the need.

## Surface

| Type | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `InternerApi` | Provider-shape trait paralleling `MemoryProviderApi` / `ClockApi`. Methods `intern(&str) -> Str`, `resolve(Str) -> Maybe<&str>`. |
| `HasInterner` | Accessor trait for the Context-provider tuple. Mirrors `HasMemoryProvider` / `HasClock`. |
| `MemoryArena<CAP, ENTRIES>` | Inline-storage `ArenaInterner` impl. Const-generic byte-cap and entry-cap. Backs the v0 default `StringInterner`. |
| `InternerKit<CAP, ENTRIES>` | `Kit<B>` impl that registers `Resource<StringInterner<MemoryArena<CAP, ENTRIES>>>` on the builder. |

### `InternerApi`

The provider shape. WorkUnits that handle `Str` (lexers, file
walkers, diagnostic emitters, etc.) declare `HasInterner` in their
`Ctx` tuple bound and call `ctx.interner().intern(s)` /
`ctx.interner().resolve(handle)` from within `execute()`.

The trait carries `Send + Sync + 'static` so the value can live
in a `Resource<T>` accessed across phase boundaries.

### `HasInterner`

```rust
pub trait HasInterner {
    type Provider: InternerApi;
    fn interner(&self) -> &Self::Provider;
}
```

The accessor lives in providers, not in api. The platform
contracts in api (memory / threadpool / clock) are the
engine-required surfaces; the interner is an opt-in provider, not
an engine prerequisite.

### `MemoryArena<CAP, ENTRIES>`

Inline-storage `ArenaInterner` impl. Holds `[u8; CAP]` bytes plus
an `[Entry; ENTRIES]` table where each entry records `(offset,
len)` for a previously-interned string. Interior mutability via
`Cell` for the cursor and entry count, `UnsafeCell` for the
buffer and table.

Each runtime-interned string gets a sequential 28-bit id (the
entry index). `arena_resolve(id)` looks up the entry and slices
`[offset..offset+len]` from the byte buffer.

Capacity overflow (out of bytes or out of entry slots) returns
sentinel id `u32::MAX` from `arena_intern`. `StringInterner`
already returns `Maybe::Isnt` from `resolve` for unresolvable
ids, so the failure path is observable. Consumers tune `CAP` and
`ENTRIES` to their workload.

`MemoryArena` is `!Sync` by default. The eventual
`Resource<StringInterner<MemoryArena<...>>>` will need either a
consumer-supplied Mutex shim or a future SyncArena variant for
multi-thread access. Tracked in BACKLOG.

### `InternerKit<CAP, ENTRIES>`

`Kit<B>` impl with a one-line `install` body:

```rust
impl<B, const CAP: usize, const ENTRIES: usize> Kit<B>
    for InternerKit<CAP, ENTRIES>
where
    B: BuilderResource<StringInterner<MemoryArena<CAP, ENTRIES>>>,
{
    type Output = B::WithResource;
    fn install(self, builder: B) -> Self::Output {
        builder.resource(StringInterner::new(MemoryArena::new()))
    }
}
```

(The `BuilderResource` trait shape is the engine's
`SchedulerBuilder::resource` method, exposed via the
`BuilderExtending` machinery from #255.)

## What v0 deliberately does not ship

- **`M: HasMemoryProvider` parameter on `MemoryArena`.** The
  original 2026-05-01 task description named `MemoryArena<M, CAP>`
  parameterised over a runtime memory provider. v0 uses inline
  storage at the type level instead. Reintroducing the M parameter
  needs allocate-at-builder-time plumbing the substrate does not
  yet have. Tracked in BACKLOG.
- **ColumnStorage / Clock / MemoryProvider defaults.** Per task
  scope: v0 is interner-only.

